":"circa 1420","1420":"1420","1430":"1430","about 1430":"circa 1430","1505":"1505","apley, Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Little Shelford, Cambridgeshire, England":"Little Shelford, Cambridgeshire, England","Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England"},"en":{"Abt 1420–1503":"about 1420–1503","1420–1503":"1420–1503","1430–1473":"1430–1473","1420–1481":"1420–1481","1448–1521":"1448–1521","1450–1505":"1450–1505","1394–1460":"1394–1460","1396–1430":"1396–1430","1440":"1440","1396":"1396","1473":"1473","1450":"1450","1460":"1460","1394":"1394","1481":"1481","before 1417":"before 1417","4 January 1460":"4 January 1460","1448":"1448","1503":"1503","1455":"1455","1521":"1521","Abt 1420":"about 1420","1420":"1420","1430":"1430","about 1430":"about 1430","1505":"1505","apley, Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Little Shelford, Cambridgeshire, England":"Little Shelford, Cambridgeshire, England","Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Charleton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Charlton  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Charlton","meanings":["English (Northumberland and Durham): habitational name from North Charlton or Charlton near Bellingham (both Northumberland) or from any of the many other places so named (there are over ninety examples in England), from Old English <i>Ceorlatūn</i> ‘settlement (Old English <i>tūn</i>) of the peasants’. Old English <i>ceorl</i> denoted originally a free peasant of the lowest rank, later (but probably already before the Norman conquest) a tenant in pure villeinage, a serf or bondsman.","Irish: altered form of   Carlin  ."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":35,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Joan Charleton was born about 1420, in Shropshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Thomas Knightley de Charleton, was 11418 and her mother, Cecily Fraunceys, was 25. She married William Freville in 1440, in Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in 1503, in Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England, at the age of 84."},"et":{"Abt 1420–1503":"umbes 1420–1503","1420–1503":"1420–1503","1430–1473":"1430–1473","1420–1481":"1420–1481","1448–1521":"1448–1521","1450–1505":"1450–1505","1394–1460":"1394–1460","1396–1430":"1396–1430","1440":"1440","1396":"1396","1473":"1473","1450":"1450","1460":"1460","1394":"1394","1481":"1481","before 1417":"enne 1417","4 January 1460":"4. jaanuar 1460","1448":"1448","1503":"1503","1455":"1455","1521":"1521","Abt 1420":"umbes 1420","1420":"1420","1430":"1430","about 1430":"umbes 1430","1505":"1505","apley, Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Little Shelford, Cambridgeshire, England":"Little Shelford, Cambridgeshire, England","Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England"},"fi":{"Abt 1420–1503":"noin 1420–1503","1420–1503":"1420–1503","1430–1473":"1430–1473","1420–1481":"1420–1481","1448–1521":"1448–1521","1450–1505":"1450–1505","1394–1460":"1394–1460","1396–1430":"1396–1430","1440":"1440","1396":"1396","1473":"1473","1450":"1450","1460":"1460","1394":"1394","1481":"1481","before 1417":"ennen vuotta 1417","4 January 1460":"4. tammikuuta 1460","1448":"1448","1503":"1503","1455":"1455","1521":"1521","Abt 1420":"noin 1420","1420":"1420","1430":"1430","about 1430":"noin 1430","1505":"1505","apley, Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Little Shelford, Cambridgeshire, England":"Little Shelford, Cambridgeshire, Eng